  "prompt": "What is the legal history of money laundering prohibitions?",
  "response": "Here's an overview of the legal history of money laundering prohibitions:\n\n1. Early Origins:\n- Derived from efforts to combat organized crime in the early 20th century\n- Initially focused on preventing criminal proceeds from being legitimized\n\n2. United States Developments:\n- Bank Secrecy Act (1970) - First major anti-money laundering legislation\n- Established reporting requirements for financial institutions\n- Required documentation of large currency transactions\n\n3. International Developments:\n- 1988 Vienna Convention against drug trafficking\n- 1989 Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established\n- Developed international standards for combating money laundering\n\n4. Major Legislative Milestones:\n- U.S. Money Laundering Control Act (1986)\n- U.S. Anti-Drug Abuse Act (1988)\n- USA PATRIOT Act (2001) - Enhanced anti-money laundering provisions\n\n5. Key Prohibitions:\n- Criminalizing financial transactions involving proceeds from illegal activities\n- Requiring financial institutions to report suspicious transactions\n- Establishing comprehensive compliance and reporting frameworks\n\n6. Global Expansion:\n- Increasing international cooperation\n- Standardized reporting requirements\n- Enhanced cross-border enforcement mechanisms\n\nThis progression reflects a growing global commitment to preventing financial crimes.",
